source.Name: Total population
source.Summary: Population: Total population and distribution by age and sex estimated to be consistent with the population by age and sex of the (a) 1950, 1960, 1970, 1983-1985, 2014 censuses; (b) adjusted for under/over count; (c) adjusted for age heaping; (d) adjusted for under enumeration of children under age 15; (e) official estimates through 2022; (f) only total population for 1983-1985 Census; and with estimates of the subsequent trends in fertility, mortality and international migration.

source.Name: Total fertility rate
source.Summary: Fertility: Total fertility rate and age pattern of fertility based on: (a) birth-histories data from the 2006-2007, 2011 MIS and 2015-2016 DHS; (b) births in the household in the preceding 12 (or 24) months classified by age of mother from the 1996, 2001 MICS and 2014 Census; (c) indirect estimates obtained from the application of the reverse survival method to the 1950, 1960, 1970, 2014 censuses and 1958-2004 Education Stats and 2001 MICS and 2006-2007 MIS; (d) indirect estimates obtained from stable population assumption; (e) cohort-completed fertility backdated by the mean age of childbearing from the 1950 Census and 2001 MICS and 2006-2007, 2011 MIS and 2015-2016 DHS.

source.Name: Life expectancy at birth
source.Summary: Overall Mortality: Life expectancy at birth and age pattern of mortality based on: (a) The demographic impact of AIDS has been factored into the mortality estimates; (b) estimates using HIV/AIDS model life tables and estimates of infant and under-five mortality (5q0), and adult mortality (45q15). In addition, the registered deaths by age and sex available through 2022 have been considered. Mortality rates for Spectrum were calculated by removing AIM's estimates of HIV-related mortality from all-cause mortality rate estimates published in the 2024 revision of the World Population Prospects.

source.Name: Age Mortality
source.Summary: Adult and Old Age Mortality: Estimates derived from: (a) siblings deaths from the 2015-2016 DHS; (b) maternal orphanhood from the 1996, 2001 MICS and 2008-2009 IBEP-MICS and 2014 Census and 2015-2016 DHS; (c) paternal orphanhood from the 1996, 2001 MICS and 2014 Census and 2015-2016 DHS; (d) intercensal survivorship from successive census age distributions; (e) estimates of under-five, adult and old age mortality. In addition, the (a) recent household deaths data by age and sex from the 2014 Census; (b) paternal orphanhood from the 2008-2009 IBEP-MICS; (c) indirect estimates of male adult mortality based on female widowhood data from the 1970, 2014 censuses and 2001 MICS and 2015-2016 DHS; (d) indirect estimates of female adult mortality based on male widowhood data from the 1970, 2014 censuses and 2001 MICS and 2015-2016 DHS have been considered.

source.Name: Infant/child mortality
source.Summary: Child Mortality: Under-five mortality based on: (a) direct estimates from births and deaths under-five calculated from full birth histories data from the 2015-2016 DHS; (b) indirect estimates from data on children ever born and surviving from the 1996, 2001 MICS and 2006-2007 MIS and 2008-2009 IBEP-MICS; (c) International estimates used up to 2021. In addition, the (a) direct estimates from births and deaths under-five calculated from full birth histories data from the 2011 MIS; (b) indirect estimates from data on children ever born and surviving from the 2014 Census; (c) recent household deaths from the 2014 Census have been considered.

source.Name: International migration
source.Summary: Migration: International migration based on: (a) information on foreign-born populations from censuses and registers from major countries of destination; (b) estimates derived as the differences between overall population growth and natural increase; (c) UNHCR statistics on the number of refugees in the main countries of asylum.
